 eighteenth century. This book addresses that gap, elaborating the extent to which artworks and practices of the fifteenth through the eighteenth centuries were accompanied by an immense range of discussions about the arts and their relation to one another.Rather than take art as a stand-in for or reflection of some other historical event or social phenomenon, this book treats art as a phenomenon in itself. The contributors suggest ways in which artworks and practices of the early modern period make aesthetic experience central to philosophical reflection, while also showing art's need for philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAesthetics, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aAesthetics, Modern. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aArt.  aEarly Modern.  aGerman.  aPhilosophy.  aRenaissance.1 aBernstein, J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCascardi, Anthony J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutrofello, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelbeke, Maarten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisendrath, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGjesdal, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoehr, Lydia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKottman, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators